  <title><ph keyref="product"/> Installer Command Line Reference</title>
  <shortdesc>Command line options of the <ph keyref="product"/> installer.</shortdesc>
  <refbody>
    <section>
      <title>The response.varfile</title>
      <p>The <ph keyref="product"/> installers for Windows and Linux creates a file called
          <filepath>response.varfile</filepath>, which records the choices that the user made when
        running the installer interactively. You can use an <filepath>response.varfile</filepath> to
        set the options for an unintended install. Here is an example of a
          <filepath>responses.varfile</filepath>:</p>
      <codeblock>#install4j response file for Oxygen XML Editor 16.0
#Fri Jul 18 21:52:15 EDT 2014
sys.adminRights$Boolean=true
sys.programGroupDisabled$Boolean=false
createDesktopLinkAction$Boolean=true
autoVersionChecking=true
sys.fileAssociation.launchers$StringArray="19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19","19"
sys.programGroupAllUsers$Boolean=true
reportProblem=true
downloadResources=true
sys.languageId=en
sys.installationDir=C\:\\Program Files (x86)\\Oxygen XML Editor 16
createQuicklaunchIconAction$Boolean=true
sys.programGroupName=Oxygen XML Editor 16.0
executeLauncherAction$Boolean=true
sys.fileAssociation.extensions$StringArray="xml","dita","ditamap","ditaval","xsl","xslt","xspec","xsd","rng","rnc","sch","dtd","mod","ent","nvdl","fo","wsdl","xquery","xq","xqy","xqm","xql","xpl","css","json","xpr"</codeblock>
      <p>The following table describes some of the settings that can be used in the
          <filepath>responses.varfile</filepath>:</p>
      <table frame="all" id="table_ncm_v3r_x4">
        <title><?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T173409-0400" comment="Why are these referred to as &quot;privacy options&quot;? Only usageDataCollector seems to have anything to do with privacy. What is the reason for documenting these particular options and not the others?"?><?oxy_comment_start author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T164741+0300" comment="Some customers did not want their users to send any kind of information, including problem reports or version information.
UsageDataCollector was removed in the meantime to avoid possible problems with such customers." mid="1"?>Privacy
          Options<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_comment_end mid="1"?> Parameters</title>
        <tgroup cols="3">
          <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
          <colspec colname="newCol2" colnum="2" colwidth="2.55*"/>
          <colspec colname="c2" colnum="3" colwidth="2.27*"/>
          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry>Parameter name</entry>
              <entry>Description</entry>
              <entry>Values</entry>
            </row>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry>autoVersionChecking</entry>
              <entry>Automatic version checking.</entry>
              <entry><codeph>true</codeph> / <codeph>false</codeph>. Default setting is
                  <codeph>true</codeph>.</entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry>reportProblem</entry>
              <entry>Allows you to report a problem encountered while using <ph keyref="product"
                />.</entry>
              <entry><codeph>true</codeph> / <codeph>false</codeph>. Default setting is
                  <codeph>true</codeph>.</entry>
            </row>
            <?oxy_insert_start author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T165155+0300"?>
            <row>
              <entry>downloadResources</entry>
              <entry>Allows <ph keyref="product"/> to download resources (links to video
                demonstrations, webinars and upcoming events) from the oXygen website in order to
                populate the application welcome screen.</entry>
              <entry><codeph>true</codeph> / <codeph>false</codeph>. Default setting is
                  <codeph>true</codeph>.</entry>
            </row>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>
            <row>
              <entry><?oxy_delete author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T164755+0300" content="usageDataCollector"?></entry>
              <entry><?oxy_delete author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T164755+0300" content="When set to &lt;codeph&gt;true&lt;/codeph&gt;, you can choose whether &lt;ph keyref=&quot;product&quot;/&gt; sends anonymous information about how it is used."?></entry>
              <entry><?oxy_delete author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T164755+0300" content="&lt;codeph&gt;true&lt;/codeph&gt; / &lt;codeph&gt;false&lt;/codeph&gt;. Default setting is &lt;codeph&gt;true&lt;/codeph&gt;."?></entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>
      <p>The <ph keyref="product"/> installation uses the install4j installer. A description of
          <xref
          href="http://resources.ej-technologies.com/install4j/help/doc/indexRedirect.html?http&amp;resources.ej-technologies.com/install4j/help/doc/helptopics/installers/responseFile.html"
          format="html" scope="external">the responses.varfile format</xref> can be found on the
        install4j site.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <title>Command line parameters</title>
      <p>The <ph keyref="product"/> installer supports the following command line parameters:</p>
      <simpletable frame="all" id="simpletable_m4s_cjr_x4">
        <sthead>
          <stentry>Option</stentry>
          <stentry>Meaning</stentry>
        </sthead>
        <strow>
          <stentry>-q</stentry>
          <stentry>Run the installer in unattended mode. The installer will not prompt the user for
            input during the install. Default settings will be used for all options unless a
            responses.varfile is specified using the -varfile option or individual settings are
            specified using <dl>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Windows: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallWindows"/> -q </codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Linux: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> -q </codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
            </dl></stentry>
        </strow>
        <strow>
          <stentry>-overwrite</stentry>
          <stentry>In unattended mode, the installer does not overwrite files with the same name if
            a previous version of the <ph keyref="product"/> is installed in the same folder. The
              <parmname>-overwrite</parmname> parameter added after the <parmname>-q</parmname>
            parameter
            <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T173433-0400" comment="What is the consequence of this failure to overwrite. Will the install fails when the file cannot be overwritten? Or will it silently create an invalid install?"?><?oxy_comment_start author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T170521+0300" comment="It depends on the behaviour of the install4J component. As far as we know, it silently logs the error. To be verified." mid="3"?>forces
            the overwriting of these files.<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_comment_end mid="3"?>
            <dl>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Windows: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallWindows"/> -q -overwrite</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Linux: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> -q -overwrite</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
            </dl></stentry>
        </strow>
        <strow>
          <stentry>-console</stentry>
          <stentry>
            <p><?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T173453-0400" comment="Why does the console version of the command line start with start /wait. Is this required to make the console stay open so you can inspect the result?"?><?oxy_comment_start author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T171839+0300" comment="install4J manual states about running the install in console mode that &quot;GUI executables are started in the background by default, therefore you have to use the start command like this to start it in the foreground and be able to enter information:
start /wait installer.exe -c &quot;

Also worth mentioning, &apos;start /wait&apos; is only available in for Windows and can be used in the middle of a batch script among other steps to keep the script execution in sequence. Otherwise the installer will start and the script will continue to execute the next command without waiting for it." mid="5"?>To
              display a console<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_comment_end mid="5"?> for the unattended
              installation, add a <parmname>-console</parmname> parameter to the command line. <dl>
                <dlentry>
                  <dt>- on Windows: </dt>
                  <dd>
                    <p>
                      <codeblock>start /wait <ph keyref="executableInstallWindows"/> -q -console</codeblock>
                    </p>
                  </dd>
                </dlentry>
                <dlentry>
                  <dt>- on Linux: </dt>
                  <dd>
                    <p>
                      <codeblock><?oxy_delete author="bogdan" timestamp="20140731T171845+0300" content="start /wait "?><?oxy_attributes keyref="&lt;change type=&quot;modified&quot; oldValue=&quot;executableInstallWindows&quot; author=&quot;bogdan&quot; timestamp=&quot;20140731T171930+0300&quot; /&gt;"?><ph keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> -q -console</codeblock>
                    </p>
                  </dd>
                </dlentry>
              </dl></p>
          </stentry>
        </strow>
        <strow>
          <stentry>-varfile</stentry>
          <stentry>Points to the location of a responses.varfile to be used during an unattended
            installation. For example:<dl>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Windows: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallWindows"/> -q -varfile response.varfile</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Linux: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><ph keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> -q -varfile response.varfile</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
            </dl></stentry>
        </strow>
        <strow>
          <stentry>-V</stentry>
          <stentry>Is used to define a variable to be used by an uattended installation. For example:<dl>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Windows: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><keyword keyref="executableInstallWindows"/> -q -VusageDataCollector=false</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
              <dlentry>
                <dt>- on Linux: </dt>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <codeblock><keyword keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> -q -VusageDataCollector=false</codeblock>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dlentry>
            </dl></stentry>
        </strow>
      </simpletable>
      <p>The <ph keyref="product"/> installation uses the install4j installer. A full list of the
          <xref
          href="http://resources.ej-technologies.com/install4j/help/doc/indexRedirect.html?http&amp;resources.ej-technologies.com/install4j/help/doc/helptopics/installers/responseFile.html"
          format="html" scope="external">command line parameters supported by the install4j
          instller</xref> can be found on the install4j site. </p>

    </section>
